## yawn.bot

yawn.bot is a draft-PR observer for the .yawn repo.

It may:

- scan .yawn files
- detect repeated inferences
- surface lacuna and objections
- open draft PR proposals
- record proof and replay

It must not:

- merge
- mark itself ready
- leak private context
- erase objections
- treat one signal as canon
- act without boundary

Service files:

```text
agents/yawn.bot.yawn
agents/yawn.bot.policy.yawn
automation/yawn.bot.daily.yawn
automation/yawn.bot.feedback-loop.yawn
automation/yawn.bot.private-pr-loop.yawn
automation/yawn.bot.ai-writing-scan.yawn
records/yawn.bot-log.yawn
```

yawn.bot is an architecture observer, not an autonomous maintainer. It can
inspect, classify, recommend, maintain ledgers, and prepare private draft PR
proposals. It does not secretly become a GitHub account, install an app, push
to main, mark PRs ready, approve, merge, send email, write a database, or
rewrite canon without current human authorization and proof.

## open-source agent contributors

This repo should be easy for humans and AI-assisted contributors to improve.

If someone has an AI workflow that can help YAWN, they should be able to show:

```text
what mission the agent helps with
what architecture it uses
what files or surfaces it reads
what it can write or propose
what proof keeps it honest
what human approval it needs
```

Contribution files:

```text
contributing.md
.github/ISSUE_TEMPLATE/ai-agent-contributor.yml
agents/contributor-agent.yawn
agents/contributor-architecture.yawn
automation/github-feedback-triage.yawn
```

## larger purpose

YAWN is an observer protocol for lived reality.

It helps people and agents record what they are inferring, compare those
inferences, protect agency, test movement with proof, and replay what changed.

Not forcing agreement.

Making disagreement legible.

That is the altruistic bet.

## first move

Create one file:

```text
first-yawn.yawn
```

Write:

```yaml
title: "my first yawn"

signal: "something has my attention"
inference: "i may be missing a small next step"

current: "something has my attention"
possible: "i can see it more clearly"
lacuna: "i do not yet know what is missing"

boundary: "do not force an answer"
move: "pause and name the signal"
proof: "i can name one clearer question"
replay: "what changed after naming it?"
```

That is enough.

## final lock

.yawn is a plain-text inference filesystem for agency.

It is how a human or agent can say:

```text
i am observing this
this is the inference
this is the missing bridge
this is the bounded move
this is the proof
this is what changed
```

That is what we are doing.
